2011-07-06T03:34:17Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-06/idea-cellular-larsen-toubro-india-stocks-preview-correct-.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes in  India  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and share prices are as of the last close, unless
otherwise stated.  The Bombay Stock Exchange Sensitive Index, or Sensex, fell
0.4 percent to 18,744.56. The BSE 200 Index slid 0.3 percent to
2,322.37. The S&P CNX Nifty Index on the National Stock Exchange
declined 0.3 percent to 5,632.10. SGX S&P CNX Nifty Index
futures for July delivery fell 0.1 percent to 5,644 as of 11:18
a.m. in  Singapore .  Cairn India Ltd. (CAIR)  : The oil and gas explorer was
cut to “hold” from “buy” at BNP Paribas, which also reduced
its share-price estimate to 325 rupees from 347 rupees. The
stock sank 3.4 percent to 312.85 rupees.  ECE Industries Ltd. (ECE)  : An electrical equipment
supplier said it will pay up to 145 rupees a share to buy back
as much as 8.42 percent of its equity capital. ECE made the
announcement in an advertisement in the Business Standard
newspaper today. ECE gained 2.7 percent to 126.1 rupees.  Godrej Consumer Products Ltd. (GCPL)  : The Indian
consumer company and US-based chocolate and confectionery maker
Hershey Co. have called off their joint venture in India, the
Economic Times reported without saying where it got the
information. Both company have agreed to call off the
partnership following which Hershey’s will sell its 51 percent
stake to Godrej Consumer for an undisclosed amount, the report
said. Godrej Consumer climbed 1.5 percent to 438.1 rupees.  Idea Cellular Ltd. (IDEA)  : India’s Telecom Disputes
Settlement and Appellate Tribunal halted the government from
imposing a fine of 2.5 billion rupees ($56 million) on Idea
Cellular for overlapping wireless permits following a planned
merger with Spice Communications Ltd. The stock fell 2.4 percent
to 77 rupees.  Larsen & Toubro Ltd. (LT)  : India’s biggest builder of
power networks and refineries expects to boost overseas orders
to 25 percent of total contracts in three years, compared with
less than 10 percent now, Chief Financial Officer Y.M. Deosthalee said in a July 4 interview at the company’s Mumbai
head office. The shares climbed 0.1 percent to 1,791.6 rupees.  Phoenix Mills Ltd. (PHNX)  : The developer is planning to
expand by setting up shopping malls in major cities like Mumbai,
Bangalore and Chennai by March 2012, the Business Standard
reported citing managing director Atul Ruia. The shares dropped
1.2 percent to 194.15 rupees.  To contact the reporters on this story:
Andrew Macaskill in  New Delhi  at 
 amacaskill@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
